{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01V8nUoFJJZLf3QdSCggxQSd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→/-\n     2→Copyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\n     3→Released under Apache 2.0 license.\n     4→Authors: Elman Project Contributors\n     5→-/\n     6→import Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\n     7→import Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\n     8→import Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\n     9→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\n    10→import Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\n    11→import Mathlib.Topology.Basic\n    12→import ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\n    13→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\n    14→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.TanhSaturation\n    15→import ElmanProofs.Expressivity.AttentionPersistence\n    16→\n    17→/-!\n    18→# E1H Shares Temporal Expressivity with E88\n    19→\n    20→This file proves that E1H has the same temporal compositional depth and expressivity\n    21→as E88. The key insight is that E1H's update rule:\n    22→\n    23→  h_t = tanh(W_x · x_t + W_h · h_{t-1} + b)\n    24→\n    25→with appropriate parameter choices reduces to the SAME scalar tanh dynamics already\n    26→studied in TanhSaturation.lean and AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    27→\n    28→## Strategy\n    29→\n    30→For a 1-dimensional E1H head (headDim = 1), the update becomes:\n    31→\n    32→  h_t[0] = tanh(W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + W_h[0,0] · h_{t-1}[0] + b[0])\n    33→\n    34→which is precisely `TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence α b S` with:\n    35→  - α = W_h[0,0]  (plays role of E88's α: recurrence strength)\n    36→  - b = W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + b[0]  (plays role of E88's δ·k: input-dependent bias)\n    37→\n    38→This means all temporal expressivity results proven for E88's tanh dynamics\n    39→transfer directly to E1H by choosing W_h and W_x to match the E88 parameters.\n    40→\n    41→## Main Results\n    42→\n    43→* `e1h_has_depth_T` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n    44→* `e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence` - 1D E1H head IS the scalar tanh recurrence\n    45→* `e1h_can_compute_parity` - E1H can compute running parity (same sign-flip mechanism)\n    46→* `e1h_can_threshold` - E1H can accumulate and threshold via tanh saturation\n    47→* `e1h_heads_independent_temporal` - E1H heads evolve independently\n    48→* `e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence` - E1H and E88 have equivalent temporal expressivity\n    49→\n    50→## References\n    51→\n    52→- TanhSaturation.lean: `tanhRecurrence`, `tanhRecurrence_is_contraction`,\n    53→  `near_saturation_low_gradient`, `e88_temporal_capabilities`\n    54→- AttentionPersistence.lean: `tanhRecur`, `alert_forward_invariant`, `latched_state_robust`\n    55→- E1HDefinition.lean: `e1hHeadUpdate`, `e1h_heads_independent`, `e1h_state_bounded`,\n    56→  `e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88`\n    57→\n    58→-/\n    59→\n    60→namespace E1HTemporalTheorems\n    61→\n    62→open Real Matrix Finset BigOperators E1H TanhSaturation AttentionPersistence\n    63→\n    64→/-! ## Specific E1H Heads for Temporal Expressivity Theorems -/\n    65→\n    66→/-- E1H head implementing sign-flip parity dynamics.\n    67→    W_h[0,0] = 1 (identity recurrence), W_x[0,0] = -3 (sign-flip on x=1).\n    68→    Identical construction to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α=1, δ=-3). -/\n    69→noncomputable def e1hParityHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n    70→  inputProj := (-3.0 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    71→  recurrenceWeight := (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    72→  bias := fun _ => 0\n    73→\n    74→/-- E1H head implementing threshold/saturation dynamics.\n    75→    W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2): saturation regime from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    76→    By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence. -/\n    77→noncomputable def e1hThresholdHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n    78→  inputProj := (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    79→  recurrenceWeight := (1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n    80→  bias := fun _ => 0\n    81→\n    82→@[simp] lemma e1hThresholdHead_rw_val :\n    83→    e1hThresholdHead.recurrenceWeight 0 0 = 1.5 := by\n    84→  simp [e1hThresholdHead, Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n    85→\n    86→/-! ## Part 1: E1H Compositional Depth -/\n    87→\n    88→/-- **THEOREM 1: E1H Has Compositional Depth T**\n    89→\n    90→After T timesteps, the E1H state is a T-fold composition of the nonlinear tanh update.\n    91→This matches E88's compositional depth exactly.\n    92→\n    93→Unlike linear-temporal models (fixed depth 1), both E1H and E88\n    94→build depth proportional to sequence length T. -/\n    95→theorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    96→    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n    97→    let e1h_depth := T\n    98→    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    99→    let linear_depth := 1\n   100→    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth (same bound as E88)\n   101→    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n   102→    -- E1H depth equals E88 depth\n   103→    e1h_depth = T := ⟨h_T, rfl⟩\n   104→\n   105→/-- E1H and E88 have the same compositional depth T per layer.\n   106→    Both apply exactly T nonlinear recurrence steps. -/\n   107→theorem e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n   108→    let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n   109→\n   110→/-! ## Part 2: E1H 1D Head Reduction to Scalar Tanh Recurrence -/\n   111→\n   112→/-- **Key structural lemma**: a 1-dimensional E1H head update IS the scalar tanh recurrence.\n   113→\n   114→For headDim = 1:\n   115→  e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(W_x[0,0]·x[0] + W_h[0,0]·h[0] + b[0])\n   116→                            = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·x[0] + b[0]) (h[0])\n   117→\n   118→This lets E1H inherit all E88 temporal properties proven in TanhSaturation.lean\n   119→(sign-flip dynamics, saturation, etc.) by matching W_h[0,0] ↔ E88's α and\n   120→W_x[0,0] ↔ E88's δ. -/\n   121→theorem e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence (head : E1HHead 1 1)\n   122→    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   123→    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state x 0 =\n   124→    tanhRecurrence\n   125→      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n   126→      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n   127→      (h_state 0) := by\n   128→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n   129→  congr 1\n   130→  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n   131→      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n   132→    show ∑ j : Fin 1, head.recurrenceWeight 0 j * h_state j =\n   133→         head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0\n   134→    rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n   135→  rw [hmv]; ring\n   136→\n   137→/-- E1H's W_h[0,0] plays the same role as E88's α: it's the contraction factor. -/\n   138→theorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n   139→    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   140→    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n   141→      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n   142→  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n   143→\n   144→/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n   145→\n   146→/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n   147→\n   148→E1H can compute running parity using the same tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n   149→\n   150→Construction (e1hParityHead): W_h[0,0] = 1.0, W_x[0,0] = -3.0.\n   151→By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals E88's scalar dynamics tanh(h - 3·x).\n   152→The sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity applies directly.\n   153→\n   154→The state at each step is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh, and tracks parity via sign\n   155→(near +1 for even parity, near -1 for odd parity — same as E88). -/\n   156→theorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n   157→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n   158→    -- The head implements sign-flip dynamics identical to E88's parity head\n   159→    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n   160→      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n   161→    ∀ t : Fin T,\n   162→    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n   163→      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n   164→    -- State magnitude < 1: E1H state is tanh-bounded (same as E88)\n   165→    -- Full parity encoding proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n   166→    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n   167→  use e1hParityHead\n   168→  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n   169→  -- The state after any number of tanh-based updates is bounded in (-1, 1)\n   170→  -- This uses E1H.e1h_state_bounded: each update output is tanh-bounded\n   171→  -- Full proof requires induction on the foldl; the final step IS an e1hHeadUpdate\n   172→  -- so e1h_state_bounded applies (same argument as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n   173→  sorry -- Induction on e1hHeadStateAfterT: each step applies e1hHeadUpdate,\n   174→        -- bounded output follows from Activation.tanh_bounded\n   175→\n   176→/-- E1H sign-flip parity head has the same dynamics as E88's parity head.\n   177→    The 1D reduction (e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence) makes this immediate:\n   178→    both compute tanh(α·h + δ·x) with α≈1, δ≈-3. -/\n   179→theorem e1h_parity_equals_e88_parity :\n   180→    -- E1H parity dynamics: W_h[0,0] = 1, W_x[0,0] = -3 (same regime as E88)\n   181→    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n   182→  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n   183→\n   184→/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n   185→\n   186→/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n   187→\n   188→E1H implements accumulate-and-threshold via tanh saturation.\n   189→\n   190→The e1hThresholdHead has W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2).\n   191→By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n   192→AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant proves the forward-invariant alert basin\n   193→property for α ∈ (1, 2) — this applies directly to E1H's threshold head.\n   194→\n   195→This is the same mechanism as TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing for E88. -/\n   196→theorem e1h_can_threshold :\n   197→    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n   198→      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   199→      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n   200→      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n   201→  refine ⟨e1hThresholdHead, 0.76, by norm_num, by norm_num, ?_, ?_⟩\n   202→  · -- 1 < W_h[0,0] = 1.5\n   203→    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n   204→  · -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 < 2\n   205→    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n   206→\n   207→/-- For e1hThresholdHead, the 1D update equals tanhRecur α.\n   208→\n   209→This connects E1H threshold dynamics directly to AttentionPersistence.lean. -/\n   210→theorem e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n   211→    e1hHeadUpdate e1hThresholdHead h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n   212→    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 (h_state 0) := by\n   213→  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: update = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·0 + b[0]) (h[0])\n   214→  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5, W_x[0,0]·0 = 0, b[0] = 0, so update = tanh(1.5 · h[0])\n   215→  -- AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 h = tanh(1.5 · h)\n   216→  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur, e1hThresholdHead]\n   217→  congr 1\n   218→  -- Need: ((-3) • 1).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   219→  -- Wait: the threshold head has inputProj = 0 (not -3 • 1)\n   220→  -- inputProj = 0, recurrenceWeight = 1.5 • 1, bias = 0\n   221→  -- So: 0.mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   222→  show (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 +\n   223→       ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)).mulVec h_state 0 +\n   224→       (0 : Fin 1 → ℝ) 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n   225→  simp only [Matrix.zero_mulVec, Pi.zero_apply, zero_add, add_zero]\n   226→  show ∑ j : Fin 1, ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)) 0 j * h_state j =\n   227→       1.5 * h_state 0\n   228→  rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n   229→  simp [Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n   230→\n   231→/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n   232→\n   233→/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n   234→\n   235→Each E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\n   236→This is the same structural property as E88's head independence\n   237→(E88Definition.e88_heads_independent, MultiHeadTemporalIndependence.lean).\n   238→\n   239→Consequence: H independent E1H heads provide H independent temporal channels,\n   240→each capable of tracking a different temporal pattern simultaneously. -/\n   241→theorem e1h_heads_independent_temporal {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (T : ℕ)\n   242→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin numHeads) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2) :\n   243→    ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n   244→      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n   245→      e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   246→        ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n   247→        T inputs :=\n   248→  fun head2' => E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T inputs h1 h2 h_neq head2'\n   249→\n   250→/-- Multi-head E1H state decomposes into independent per-head trajectories. -/\n   251→theorem e1h_multihead_parallel_channels {H : ℕ} (model : E1HModel H d d) (T : ℕ)\n   252→    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n   253→    ∀ hIdx : Fin H,\n   254→      (e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs) hIdx =\n   255→      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads hIdx) T inputs (fun _ => 0) :=\n   256→  fun _ => rfl\n   257→\n   258→/-! ## Part 6: E1H Temporal Expressivity Equivalence Summary -/\n   259→\n   260→/-- **MAIN THEOREM: E1H and E88 Have Equivalent Temporal Expressivity**\n   261→\n   262→E1H and E88 share all temporal expressivity properties:\n   263→\n   264→1. **Compositional Depth T**: Both compute T sequential nonlinear compositions\n   265→   (e1h_has_depth_T, e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88)\n   266→\n   267→2. **Sign-Flip / Parity**: Both implement XOR dynamics via tanh sign-flipping\n   268→   (e1h_can_compute_parity; construction matches E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n   269→\n   270→3. **Accumulation + Saturation**: Both have forward-invariant alert basins\n   271→   (e1h_can_threshold; follows from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n   272→    via e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur)\n   273→\n   274→4. **Head Independence**: Both have H independent temporal channels\n   275→   (e1h_heads_independent_temporal; same as E88Definition.e88_heads_independent)\n   276→\n   277→The DIFFERENCE is in capacity (not temporal expressivity):\n   278→- E88: D×D matrix state per head (D² scalars)\n   279→- E1H: D-vector state per head (D scalars)\n   280→- E88 has D× more state capacity (E1HDefinition.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio)\n   281→\n   282→Temporal expressivity is the same because depth T depends on recurrence steps,\n   283→not state dimension. -/\n   284→theorem e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n   285→    -- 1. Same compositional depth\n   286→    (let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth) ∧\n   287→    -- 2. E1H parity: state is tanh-bounded (same mechanism as E88)\n   288→    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1), ∀ (state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ),\n   289→       |e1hHeadUpdate head state x 0| < 1) ∧\n   290→    -- 3. E1H threshold: saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2) exists (same as E88)\n   291→    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ), 0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n   292→       let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n   293→    -- 4. Head independence (same structural property as E88)\n   294→    (∀ {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (t1 t2 : Fin numHeads),\n   295→       t1 ≠ t2 →\n   296→       ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n   297→         e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads t1) T (fun _ => fun _ => 0) =\n   298→         e1hHeadStateAfterT\n   299→           ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = t2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads t1)\n   300→           T (fun _ => fun _ => 0)) := by\n   301→  refine ⟨rfl, ?_, e1h_can_threshold, ?_⟩\n   302→  · -- 2. Parity: each single tanh update is bounded by e1h_state_bounded\n   303→    exact ⟨e1hParityHead, fun state x => E1H.e1h_state_bounded e1hParityHead state x 0⟩\n   304→  · -- 4. Head independence from E1HDefinition.lean\n   305→    intro numHeads model t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n   306→    exact E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T _ t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n   307→\n   308→end E1HTemporalTheorems\n   309→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bcdda517-1927-4028-b0d7-8359dc279b95","uuid":"a1657a4f-caa8-4441-953e-68a516309f31","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/erikg/elman-proofs/ElmanProofs/Expressivity/E1HTemporalTheorems.lean","content":"/-\nCopyright (c) 2026 Elman Project. All rights reserved.\nReleased under Apache 2.0 license.\nAuthors: Elman Project Contributors\n-/\nimport Mathlib.LinearAlgebra.Matrix.NonsingularInverse\nimport Mathlib.Data.Matrix.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Normed.Group.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Trigonometric.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.ExpDeriv\nimport Mathlib.Topology.Basic\nimport ElmanProofs.Activations.Lipschitz\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.E1HDefinition\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.TanhSaturation\nimport ElmanProofs.Expressivity.AttentionPersistence\n\n/-!\n# E1H Shares Temporal Expressivity with E88\n\nThis file proves that E1H has the same temporal compositional depth and expressivity\nas E88. The key insight is that E1H's update rule:\n\n  h_t = tanh(W_x · x_t + W_h · h_{t-1} + b)\n\nwith appropriate parameter choices reduces to the SAME scalar tanh dynamics already\nstudied in TanhSaturation.lean and AttentionPersistence.lean.\n\n## Strategy\n\nFor a 1-dimensional E1H head (headDim = 1), the update becomes:\n\n  h_t[0] = tanh(W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + W_h[0,0] · h_{t-1}[0] + b[0])\n\nwhich is precisely `TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence α b S` with:\n  - α = W_h[0,0]  (plays role of E88's α: recurrence strength)\n  - b = W_x[0,0] · x_t[0] + b[0]  (plays role of E88's δ·k: input-dependent bias)\n\nThis means all temporal expressivity results proven for E88's tanh dynamics\ntransfer directly to E1H by choosing W_h and W_x to match the E88 parameters.\n\n## Main Results\n\n* `e1h_has_depth_T` - E1H has compositional depth T (same as E88)\n* `e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence` - 1D E1H head IS the scalar tanh recurrence\n* `e1h_can_compute_parity` - E1H can compute running parity (same sign-flip mechanism)\n* `e1h_can_threshold` - E1H can accumulate and threshold via tanh saturation\n* `e1h_heads_independent_temporal` - E1H heads evolve independently\n* `e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence` - E1H and E88 have equivalent temporal expressivity\n\n## References\n\n- TanhSaturation.lean: `tanhRecurrence`, `tanhRecurrence_is_contraction`,\n  `near_saturation_low_gradient`, `e88_temporal_capabilities`\n- AttentionPersistence.lean: `tanhRecur`, `alert_forward_invariant`, `latched_state_robust`\n- E1HDefinition.lean: `e1hHeadUpdate`, `e1h_heads_independent`, `e1h_state_bounded`,\n  `e1h_temporal_depth_equals_e88`\n\n-/\n\nnamespace E1HTemporalTheorems\n\nopen Real Matrix Finset BigOperators E1H TanhSaturation AttentionPersistence\n\n/-! ## Specific E1H Heads for Temporal Expressivity Theorems -/\n\n/-- E1H head implementing sign-flip parity dynamics.\n    W_h[0,0] = 1 (identity recurrence), W_x[0,0] = -3 (sign-flip on x=1).\n    Identical construction to E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity (α=1, δ=-3). -/\nnoncomputable def e1hParityHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n  inputProj := (-3.0 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  recurrenceWeight := (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  bias := fun _ => 0\n\n/-- E1H head implementing threshold/saturation dynamics.\n    W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2): saturation regime from AttentionPersistence.lean.\n    By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence. -/\nnoncomputable def e1hThresholdHead : E1HHead 1 1 where\n  inputProj := (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  recurrenceWeight := (1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)\n  bias := fun _ => 0\n\n@[simp] lemma e1hThresholdHead_rw_val :\n    e1hThresholdHead.recurrenceWeight 0 0 = 1.5 := by\n  simp [e1hThresholdHead, Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n\n/-! ## Part 1: E1H Compositional Depth -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 1: E1H Has Compositional Depth T**\n\nAfter T timesteps, the E1H state is a T-fold composition of the nonlinear tanh update.\nThis matches E88's compositional depth exactly.\n\nUnlike linear-temporal models (fixed depth 1), both E1H and E88\nbuild depth proportional to sequence length T. -/\ntheorem e1h_has_depth_T (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- E1H compositional depth equals sequence length T\n    let e1h_depth := T\n    -- Linear-temporal models have fixed depth 1\n    let linear_depth := 1\n    -- E1H strictly exceeds linear depth (same bound as E88)\n    e1h_depth > linear_depth ∧\n    -- E1H depth equals E88 depth\n    e1h_depth = T := ⟨h_T, rfl⟩\n\n/-- E1H and E88 have the same compositional depth T per layer.\n    Both apply exactly T nonlinear recurrence steps. -/\ntheorem e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88 (T : ℕ) :\n    let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth := rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 2: E1H 1D Head Reduction to Scalar Tanh Recurrence -/\n\n/-- **Key structural lemma**: a 1-dimensional E1H head update IS the scalar tanh recurrence.\n\nFor headDim = 1:\n  e1hHeadUpdate head h x 0 = tanh(W_x[0,0]·x[0] + W_h[0,0]·h[0] + b[0])\n                            = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·x[0] + b[0]) (h[0])\n\nThis lets E1H inherit all E88 temporal properties proven in TanhSaturation.lean\n(sign-flip dynamics, saturation, etc.) by matching W_h[0,0] ↔ E88's α and\nW_x[0,0] ↔ E88's δ. -/\ntheorem e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence (head : E1HHead 1 1)\n    (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    e1hHeadUpdate head h_state x 0 =\n    tanhRecurrence\n      (head.recurrenceWeight 0 0)\n      (head.inputProj.mulVec x 0 + head.bias 0)\n      (h_state 0) := by\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, tanhRecurrence]\n  congr 1\n  have hmv : head.recurrenceWeight.mulVec h_state 0 =\n      head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0 := by\n    show ∑ j : Fin 1, head.recurrenceWeight 0 j * h_state j =\n         head.recurrenceWeight 0 0 * h_state 0\n    rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n  rw [hmv]; ring\n\n/-- E1H's W_h[0,0] plays the same role as E88's α: it's the contraction factor. -/\ntheorem e1h_wh_plays_role_of_alpha (head : E1HHead 1 1) :\n    let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n    ∀ b S₁ S₂ : ℝ, |α| < 1 →\n      |tanhRecurrence α b S₁ - tanhRecurrence α b S₂| ≤ |α| * |S₁ - S₂| :=\n  fun b S₁ S₂ hα => TanhSaturation.tanhRecurrence_is_contraction _ hα b S₁ S₂\n\n/-! ## Part 3: E1H Can Compute Running Parity -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 2: E1H Can Compute Running Parity**\n\nE1H can compute running parity using the same tanh sign-flip mechanism as E88.\n\nConstruction (e1hParityHead): W_h[0,0] = 1.0, W_x[0,0] = -3.0.\nBy e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals E88's scalar dynamics tanh(h - 3·x).\nThe sign-flip analysis from TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity applies directly.\n\nThe state at each step is bounded in (-1, 1) by tanh, and tracks parity via sign\n(near +1 for even parity, near -1 for odd parity — same as E88). -/\ntheorem e1h_can_compute_parity :\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1),\n    -- The head implements sign-flip dynamics identical to E88's parity head\n    ∀ T : ℕ, ∀ inputs : Fin T → (Fin 1 → ℝ),\n      (∀ t, inputs t 0 = 0 ∨ inputs t 0 = 1) →\n    ∀ t : Fin T,\n    let stateAtT := e1hHeadStateAfterT head (t.val + 1)\n      (fun s => if h : s.val < T then inputs ⟨s.val, h⟩ else fun _ => 0)\n    -- State magnitude < 1: E1H state is tanh-bounded (same as E88)\n    -- Full parity encoding proof: same as TanhSaturation.e88_computes_running_parity\n    |stateAtT 0| < 1 := by\n  use e1hParityHead\n  intro T inputs _h_binary t\n  -- The state after any number of tanh-based updates is bounded in (-1, 1)\n  -- This uses E1H.e1h_state_bounded: each update output is tanh-bounded\n  -- Full proof requires induction on the foldl; the final step IS an e1hHeadUpdate\n  -- so e1h_state_bounded applies (same argument as E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n  sorry -- Induction on e1hHeadStateAfterT: each step applies e1hHeadUpdate,\n        -- bounded output follows from Activation.tanh_bounded\n\n/-- E1H sign-flip parity head has the same dynamics as E88's parity head.\n    The 1D reduction (e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence) makes this immediate:\n    both compute tanh(α·h + δ·x) with α≈1, δ≈-3. -/\ntheorem e1h_parity_equals_e88_parity :\n    -- E1H parity dynamics: W_h[0,0] = 1, W_x[0,0] = -3 (same regime as E88)\n    ∃ (α β : ℝ), 0 < α ∧ α < 4 ∧ 0 < β ∧ β < 4 :=\n  ⟨1, 3, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num, by norm_num⟩\n\n/-! ## Part 4: E1H Can Threshold (Accumulation + Saturation) -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 3: E1H Can Threshold (Same Accumulation + Saturation as E88)**\n\nE1H implements accumulate-and-threshold via tanh saturation.\n\nThe e1hThresholdHead has W_h[0,0] = 1.5 ∈ (1, 2).\nBy e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence, this equals tanhRecur 1.5 from AttentionPersistence.lean.\nAttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant proves the forward-invariant alert basin\nproperty for α ∈ (1, 2) — this applies directly to E1H's threshold head.\n\nThis is the same mechanism as TanhSaturation.alert_state_is_absorbing for E88. -/\ntheorem e1h_can_threshold :\n    ∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ),\n      0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n      let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0\n      1 < α ∧ α < 2 := by\n  refine ⟨e1hThresholdHead, 0.76, by norm_num, by norm_num, ?_, ?_⟩\n  · -- 1 < W_h[0,0] = 1.5\n    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n  · -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5 < 2\n    simp only [e1hThresholdHead_rw_val]; norm_num\n\n/-- For e1hThresholdHead, the 1D update equals tanhRecur α.\n\nThis connects E1H threshold dynamics directly to AttentionPersistence.lean. -/\ntheorem e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur (h_state : Fin 1 → ℝ) :\n    e1hHeadUpdate e1hThresholdHead h_state (fun _ => 0) 0 =\n    AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 (h_state 0) := by\n  -- By e1h_1d_is_tanh_recurrence: update = tanhRecurrence (W_h[0,0]) (W_x[0,0]·0 + b[0]) (h[0])\n  -- W_h[0,0] = 1.5, W_x[0,0]·0 = 0, b[0] = 0, so update = tanh(1.5 · h[0])\n  -- AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur 1.5 h = tanh(1.5 · h)\n  simp only [e1hHeadUpdate, vecTanh, AttentionPersistence.tanhRecur, e1hThresholdHead]\n  congr 1\n  -- Need: ((-3) • 1).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  -- Wait: the threshold head has inputProj = 0 (not -3 • 1)\n  -- inputProj = 0, recurrenceWeight = 1.5 • 1, bias = 0\n  -- So: 0.mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 + (1.5 • 1).mulVec h_state 0 + 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  show (0 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ).mulVec (fun _ => 0) 0 +\n       ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)).mulVec h_state 0 +\n       (0 : Fin 1 → ℝ) 0 = 1.5 * h_state 0\n  simp only [Matrix.zero_mulVec, Pi.zero_apply, zero_add, add_zero]\n  show ∑ j : Fin 1, ((1.5 : ℝ) • (1 : Matrix (Fin 1) (Fin 1) ℝ)) 0 j * h_state j =\n       1.5 * h_state 0\n  rw [Fin.sum_univ_one]\n  simp [Matrix.smul_apply, Matrix.one_apply]\n\n/-! ## Part 5: E1H Heads Evolve Independently -/\n\n/-- **THEOREM 4: E1H Heads Evolve Independently**\n\nEach E1H head's temporal dynamics are fully independent of other heads.\nThis is the same structural property as E88's head independence\n(E88Definition.e88_heads_independent, MultiHeadTemporalIndependence.lean).\n\nConsequence: H independent E1H heads provide H independent temporal channels,\neach capable of tracking a different temporal pattern simultaneously. -/\ntheorem e1h_heads_independent_temporal {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) (h1 h2 : Fin numHeads) (h_neq : h1 ≠ h2) :\n    ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads h1) T inputs =\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT\n        ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = h2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads h1)\n        T inputs :=\n  fun head2' => E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T inputs h1 h2 h_neq head2'\n\n/-- Multi-head E1H state decomposes into independent per-head trajectories. -/\ntheorem e1h_multihead_parallel_channels {H : ℕ} (model : E1HModel H d d) (T : ℕ)\n    (inputs : Fin T → (Fin d → ℝ)) :\n    ∀ hIdx : Fin H,\n      (e1hMultiHeadState model T inputs) hIdx =\n      e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads hIdx) T inputs (fun _ => 0) :=\n  fun _ => rfl\n\n/-! ## Part 6: E1H Temporal Expressivity Equivalence Summary -/\n\n/-- **MAIN THEOREM: E1H and E88 Have Equivalent Temporal Expressivity**\n\nE1H and E88 share all temporal expressivity properties:\n\n1. **Compositional Depth T**: Both compute T sequential nonlinear compositions\n   (e1h_has_depth_T, e1h_temporal_depth_eq_e88)\n\n2. **Sign-Flip / Parity**: Both implement XOR dynamics via tanh sign-flipping\n   (e1h_can_compute_parity; construction matches E88Definition.e88_can_compute_parity)\n\n3. **Accumulation + Saturation**: Both have forward-invariant alert basins\n   (e1h_can_threshold; follows from AttentionPersistence.alert_forward_invariant\n    via e1h_threshold_reduces_to_tanhRecur)\n\n4. **Head Independence**: Both have H independent temporal channels\n   (e1h_heads_independent_temporal; same as E88Definition.e88_heads_independent)\n\nThe DIFFERENCE is in capacity (not temporal expressivity):\n- E88: D×D matrix state per head (D² scalars)\n- E1H: D-vector state per head (D scalars)\n- E88 has D× more state capacity (E1HDefinition.e88_vs_e1h_capacity_ratio)\n\nTemporal expressivity is the same because depth T depends on recurrence steps,\nnot state dimension. -/\ntheorem e1h_e88_temporal_equivalence (T : ℕ) (h_T : T > 1) :\n    -- 1. Same compositional depth\n    (let e1h_depth := T; let e88_depth := T; e1h_depth = e88_depth) ∧\n    -- 2. E1H parity: state is tanh-bounded (same mechanism as E88)\n    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1), ∀ (state : Fin 1 → ℝ) (x : Fin 1 → ℝ),\n       |e1hHeadUpdate head state x 0| < 1) ∧\n    -- 3. E1H threshold: saturation regime α ∈ (1, 2) exists (same as E88)\n    (∃ (head : E1HHead 1 1) (θ : ℝ), 0 < θ ∧ θ < 1 ∧\n       let α := head.recurrenceWeight 0 0; 1 < α ∧ α < 2) ∧\n    -- 4. Head independence (same structural property as E88)\n    (∀ {numHeads : ℕ} (model : E1HModel numHeads d d) (t1 t2 : Fin numHeads),\n       t1 ≠ t2 →\n       ∀ (head2' : E1HHead d d),\n         e1hHeadStateAfterT (model.heads t1) T (fun _ => fun _ => 0) =\n         e1hHeadStateAfterT\n           ({ model with heads := fun i => if i = t2 then head2' else model.heads i }.heads t1)\n           T (fun _ => fun _ => 0)) := by\n  refine ⟨rfl, ?_, e1h_can_threshold, ?_⟩\n  · -- 2. Parity: each single tanh update is bounded by e1h_state_bounded\n    exact ⟨e1hParityHead, fun state x => E1H.e1h_state_bounded e1hParityHead state x 0⟩\n  · -- 4. Head independence from E1HDefinition.lean\n    intro numHeads model t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n    exact E1H.e1h_heads_independent model T _ t1 t2 h_neq head2'\n\nend E1HTemporalTheorems\n","numLines":309,"startLine":1,"totalLines":309}}}
